The flechette round carries about 9,1 inch dart shaped projectiles. In Vietnam they were used in taking out snipers hiding in thick brush or trees. Due to the penetration of these projectiles, tree limbs and brush will not disperse the darts as readily as round shot. They will give an all covering pattern within trees or brush. The Remington 788 is an accurate hunting rifle developed by the Remington Arms Company.

The 788 utilizes a single-column detachable magazine holding 4 rounds. A .22 rimfire model was also produced known as the 580, 581, or 582 depending on its method of feed.

A target version was used by the US military[2] as a training rifle and later disposed through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.

Distinguishing design characteristics
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles.
The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs. The locking bolt requires the safety to be in the "fire" or "off" position in order to rotate the handle and actuate the bolt. Rifles manufactured from 1975 to 1983 have non-locking bolts which can be actuated while the safety is engaged.
The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well.
When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength.
These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter.
A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.

Have for sale an absolute beauty of a kalashnikov. It is a bulgarian ak74 in 5.45 x 39 built by TGI. Dressed in original russian plum furniture. Gun is unfired. All numbers match. Dated 1989 and the 29 before the serial indicates that this was a limited production year. http://www.makarov.com/makfaq.html Everything is perfectly straight on this gun. No canted sights, no poor rivet work, etc. Not like the bastardized ak's you see out there.  Hate to see this one go. Price is firm. No trades. Comes with 1 30 rd mag.

In case you are not aware the AK74 was designed in 1974 and is the AK currently in use by Russian military as well as a host of other countries. This cartridge is comparable to the 556. Actually, it was developed in response to the 556. What makes this round so unique is its tendency to yaw shortly after penetrating for inflicting maximum damage. It is said that the mujahadeen nicknamed it the poison bullet for its devastating effects when they encountered it in Afghanistan. It shoots flatter than the 7.62x39 and its less recoil will allow more rounds on target than the 7.62. 

The AK74 retains all of the same reliability qualities as the AK47. More pics available upon request.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AR15 "featureless" (CA legal standard mag release button)
postcontent:
Here's a fully loaded AR15 for the firearms enthusiast who wants to stand out from the crowd. Definitely a head-turner!

A quick note on "featureless" AR15s:

In the state of California, all AR15 rifles must not have a detachable magazine. There are two ways to get around this. The first way is by installing a "bullet button". These devices only allow the magazine to be dropped by using a tool (a bullet works). Personally, I hate this. The second way is to have an AR15 that has no "evil features". This means a fixed stock, no flash hider (compensators are fine), no vertical forward grip, and no pistol grip. Buy building a featureless rifle, you're able to drop the magazine just by pushing the mag release button. This rifle is featureless. 

Build Specs:

AR FiveSeven lower
Palmetto State Armory LPK & UPK
Palmetto State Armory upper reciever
Bravo Company medium "gunfighter" charging handle
Palmetto State Armory auto-profile BCG
AR Stoner 16" barrel
Yankee Hill Machine black gas block and tube
Exile Hammerhead grip
Diamondhead VRS-T 10.25" free-flat hand guard
Magpul MOE stock
Ambidextrous safety selector
Magpul MBUS front and read sights
Primary Arms 3moa red dot sight on a cantilever mount
VG6 Gamma compensator

Comes with two Magpul 10rd. Pmags and 120 rounds of 55 grain FMJ.

This baby shoots like a dream. No muzzle rise and hardly any recoil. By installing the Exile grip, the rifle is held just like a traditional rifle. It is very comfortable to hold, and I actually prefer the Exile grip over a pistol grip.

Now you may be wondering why I'm getting rid of it if it shoots so nice. Well, I just don't really like ARs that much. It really is a fantastic gun, but I much prefer lever and bolt action rifles, auto pistols, and revolvers. 

So, what am I looking to trade for? Lots of things. 

Guns:
Ruger Gunsite Scout
Ruger Super Redhawk in 454 casull. I really want one of these guys!
S&W .500
Ruger No.1 in .45-70
Single action revolvers
CAS/SASS gear (guns and/or rigs)
What have you got? The above are just what comes to mind. Got something else you think I'll be interested in? Make an offer.

Non-guns:
I dunno. Again, open to offers.

Cash? I'll entertain all offers, but don't expect me to sell too low.

I'm not in a rush to get rid of this.
